Our main goal is to estimate from samples . This problem become non-trivial when we want to estimate distributions of complex, high-dimensional data, for example, a image lies in a -dimensional space.

In general, we want to train models that have the following properties:

efficient training and computation
expressiveness and computation
sampling quality and speed

One severe problem with such an approach is the lack of generalization, that is, the model is often the training data distribution itself, which might lead to poor generalization. We can solve this by instead learning a parameterized distributions, since fitting a parameterized distribution often generalizes better.


Recall that the ultimate goal of learning a generative model is to learn so that , i.e.:

To learn , what we can do is to pose a search problem over parameters:

We want the loss and the search procedure to (1) work with large datasets, (2) yield such that matches [1]. The procedure we will use is Maximum Likelihood Estimation (MLE).

An intuitive interpretation of MLE is that we pick the model parameters that maximize the log-probability of the observed datapoints in . As shown in Kullback-Leibler Divergence > KL Divergence and MLE, MLE is equivalent to minimizing the Kullback-Leibler Divergence between the empirical data distribution and the model [2]. We know that MLE is an optimization problem [3] and here we will solve it using Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD).


Assume we are given access to a dataset of -dimensional datapoints . For simplicity, we assume the datapoints are binary .
By the Chain rule of probability, we can factorize the joint distribution over -dimensions as:

This is guaranteed because any multivariable distribution can be written as a product of conditionals. Here, can intuitively be interpreted as the probability of the next pixel in an image given all the previous pixels. But still, the number of countings is still exponential, so we need to come up with other ways.

The chain rule factorization can also be expressed as a Bayesian network. This network makes no conditional independence assumptions and is said to obey the autoregressive property.
In an autoregressive generative model, the conditionals are specified as parameterized functions with a fixed number of parameters, i.e. we assume the conditional distributions to correspond to a Bernoulli random variable and learn a function that maps the preceeding random variables to the mean of this distribution. Hence, we have:

where denotes the set of parameters used to specify the mean function . The total number of parameters of an autoregressive generative model are given by .

Unlike the tabular setting however, an autoregressive generative model cannot represent all possible distributions. Its expressiveness is limited by the fact that we are limiting the conditional distributions. Generally, sparsification introduces strong assumptions, which can limit expressivity under a restricted class of parameterized functions. And so although Bayes' nets is efficient, in most cases it makes strong assumption, which might lead to poor fits.

Another potential method is to use neural network to approximate the conditionals. Starting from chain rule, we can approximate the true conditional using Neural network as follows:



Given a dataset of handwritten digits, where each image has 784 pixels (28 28), each pixel can either be black or white.

The goal is to learn a probability distribution over such that when we sample from , looks like a digit. This is a challenging task because there are lots of images and we need to assign the probability to each one of them.
To solve this, there are generally two steps:
(1): parameterize a model family
(2): search for model parameters based on the training data


The conditional variables are Bernoulli with parameters. We can specify the function as a linear combination of the input elements followed by a sigmoid non-linearity.

A natural way to increase the expressiveness of an autoregressive generative model is to use more flexible parameterizations for the mean function e.g., multi-layer perceptrons (MLP) instead of logistic regression. here, is the weights of the network. One potential problem is that the history keeps getting longer as the sequence becomes longer.

For a better understanding of how RNN works, readers are recommended to read a blogpost The Unreasonable Effectiveness of Recurrent Neural Networksby Andrej Karpathy.
Training a 3-layer RNN with 512 hidden nodes on all the works of Shakespeare yields:
KING LEAR: O, if you were a feeble sight, the courtesy of your law, Your sight and several breath, will wear the gods With his heads, and my hands are wonder’d at the deeds, So drop upon your lordship’s head, and your opinion Shall be against your honour. Copy
Pros

can be applied to sequences with arbitrary length
very general: for every computable computation, there exists a finite RNN that can compute it
Cons

requires an ordering
sequential (very slow for traning)
sequential generation (obvious for autoregressive model)
